[308] (9w) By 2015, the company is fully back on track.
[309] (7w) Best year ever for the LEGO Group.
[310] (27w) So, just like at the Oscars or just like in the movie theaters this last year, we are also dancing and singing and saying everything is awesome.
[311] (6w) Knudstorp pulls off an impressive turnaround.
[312] (12w) Two things bring LEGO out of crisis and back to the top.
[313] (20w) His uncompromising focus on economic success and his radically honest leadership style of openly acknowledging when the company is struggling.
[314] (19w) Journalists end up calling it the Knudstorp cure, and he won't be the last McKinsey consultant to shape LEGO.
[315] (8w) In 2017, Niels Christiansen takes over as CEO.
[316] (12w) Despite the shared last name, he's not part of the founding family.
[317] (8w) Like Knudstorp, Christiansen had previously worked at McKinsey.
[318] (12w) Before joining LEGO, he spent years running the Danish multinational company Danfoss.
[319] (10w) Now, he's determined to take LEGO to the next level.
[320] (20w) The key part of his strategy is reaching even more people around the globe, mainly by pushing into new markets.
[321] (5w) His main focus is China.
[322] (46w) A company like us that are really interested in in getting out there experiences to all kids throughout the world, to China is important with 200 million kids, of course, it's a super important market with a with with many kids that we want to reach.
[323] (9w) LEGO is now developing products specifically targeting Chinese customers.
[324] (13w) One example is the Monkey Kid series inspired by Chinese mythology and folklore.
[325] (16w) And over the next two decades, LEGO is also looking to firmly establish itself in India.
[326] (9w) Niels's biggest concern is LEGO's ability to stay relevant.
[327] (23w) He says it's the one thing keeping him awake at night, but it looks like he's found the formula to make it happen.
[328] (3w) Even more products.
[329] (17w) LEGO has released 840 sets in 2024 alone, covering every age group and every niche interest imaginable.
[330] (9w) Niels wants to complement physical play with digital experiences.
[331] (17w) And just like his predecessor, Knudstorp, the new CEO is all in on collaborations with trending brands.
[332] (7w) And he's expanding the LEGO brand itself.
[333] (11w) Today, you can buy shirts, mugs, puzzles, and brick-shaped storage boxes.
[334] (22w) There are over a thousand official LEGO stores worldwide, plus multiple indoor experiences like the LEGO Discovery Centers and the LEGO House.
[335] (10w) In 2019, the company brought back the LEGOLAND theme parks.
[336] (11w) Apart from a COVID dip, LEGO revenues just keep on climbing.
[337] (11w) Under Niels Christiansen, the company hits one sales record after another.
[338] (15w) Toy markets in Europe and America may be in decline, but LEGO continues to thrive.
[339] (12w) It's pulled far ahead of its competitors over the last few years.
[340] (12w) Today, it's by far the most valuable toy brand in the world.
[341] (17w) While LEGO's executive team is probably quite happy about all this, many long-term fans are drifting away.
[342] (14w) Criticism from both customers and fans has only grown louder under the new CEO.
[343] (8w) LEGO's prices feel too high and sometimes random.
[344] (7w) Overall product quality appears to be declining.
[345] (17w) And to many fans, it feels as if LEGO is now focusing mostly on new target groups.
[346] (27w) Many believe that LEGO's success relies not so much on the quality of its current products, but more on the cherished childhood memories associated with the brand.
[347] (16w) We reached out to LEGO for comment on all of these concerns, but never heard back.
[348] (6w) LEGO doesn't just sell toy bricks.
[349] (17w) It sells a feeling. Almost no other company in the world is so effective at monetizing nostalgia.
[350] (12w) But what nostalgic feeling will future generations of customers associate with LEGO?
[351] (10w) Maybe it'll be their own movie and TV show heroes.
[352] (12w) And maybe strong licensing deals will forever be enough. Or maybe not."
`;

