[42] (13w) All of the siblings were affected by the ailment, though to different severities.
[43] (17w) The 9 year old boy was taken to a pediatric ICU where he was ventilated and monitored.
[44] (11w) They treated him for liver failure with lactulose, neomycin, and acetylcysteine.
[45] (12w) He regained consciousness and was successfully extubated with no other major complications.
[46] (12w) The elder 2 sisters were treated with fluid resuscitation, and recovered slowly.
[47] (15w) The eldest brother was affected less severely than the others, and was kept under observation.
[48] (25w) His blood samples came back good, and he, along with his surviving brothers and sisters, were allowed to leave after 8 days in the hospital.
[49] (29w) In another case involving leftovers, a 17 year old boy and his father came down with a bout of vomiting 30 minutes after eating spaghetti served with homemade pesto.
[50] (36w) It was made about 4 days prior and put into the fridge, however it was left out at room temperature multiple times for up to 2 hours at a time before it was reheated and served.
[51] (19w) The spaghetti had an odor, but they ate all of it, however the son ate more than his father.
[52] (30w) The father was a doctor, so coming down with abdominal pain and diarrhea about 30 minutes after eating, he took a course of anti-emetics and charcoal to help his vomiting.
[53] (25w) He stabilized, but his son, who didn’t have diarrhea, continued vomiting so badly, he could not keep his charcoal down despite being given anti-emetic meds.
[54] (10w) The son’s condition slowly deteriorated over the next 2 days.
[55] (10w) His father treated him with aspirin, acetaminophen, and other medications.
[56] (6w) The efforts were in vain, however.
[57] (6w) His son became fatigued and listless.
[58] (29w) He was taken to the hospital where doctors found him to be jaundiced, his skin and eyes yellowed, as well as suffering from tachycardia, a very high heart rate.
[59] (12w) Doctors diagnosed him with fulminant hepatic failure, rhabdomyolysis, and acute renal failure.
[60] (23w) In other words, his liver was failing very quickly, his muscles were leaking into his bloodstream, and his kidneys were failing as well.
[61] (9w) All in all, a bad day wouldn’t you agree?
[62] (14w) The father still had some abdominal pain and diarrhea, but was otherwise completely fine.
[63] (7w) The son’s condition, however, continued to worsen.
[64] (18w) At the University hospital of Zurich, he wasn’t able to respond to commands, nor walk on his own.
[65] (13w) His pupils still responded to light, though, which is a win, however small.
[66] (19w) Doctors took some of the son’s blood for examination, but no toxins that would trigger liver failure were found.
[67] (19w) Medical staff also tested the blood for any nefarious bacteria and fungi, however those tests also came back negative.
[68] (16w) Doctors also determined that his liver failure was not connected to hepatitis, Epstein-Barr virus, or Herpes.
[69] (12w) The son was immediately scheduled for a liver transplant and supportive treatment.
[70] (23w) Despite this, the boy developed a brain edema, which is when fluid builds up in the skull cavity, putting pressure on the brain.
[71] (11w) This pressure built up until his brain couldn’t take any more.
[72] (9w) He died a day after arriving at the hospital.
[73] (11w) Now, I’m sure you’ve noticed some similarities between our cases already.
[74] (16w) In particular, both of the deceased, and their families, ate leftovers before coming down with symptoms.
[75] (11w) They both suffered forms of liver failure before their untimely deaths.
[76] (6w) But what could be behind this?
[77] (25w) The liver, in short, is the organ that controls the levels of particular chemicals in our blood stream, and removes any toxins or waste products.
[78] (31w) All the blood leaving your stomach and intestines, after gobbling up all the nutrients from your food, is filtered through the liver before going out to the rest of your body.
[79] (34w) It also converts various chemicals into forms that the rest of your body can use, so without it, your body is unable to get many of the nutrients it needs from your digestive system.
[80] (8w) Nutrients that your body needs to, y’know, live.
[81] (20w) The autopsy on the young girl found cultures of a bacteria called Bacillus cereus in her gut, and her spleen.
[82] (25w) Medical staff also performed a liver biopsy, and found that her liver was severely necrotic, the very cells that made up her liver were dying.
[83] (28w) Upon testing the food she’d eaten, and her vomit, doctors found more cultures of B. cereus, lending credence to their theory that the foodborne pathogen had killed her.
[84] (13w) In short, bacteria in her food shut down her liver, taking her life.
[85] (22w) In the autopsy on the 17 year old, after a liver biopsy, doctors found high concentrations of, you guessed it, B. cereus!
[86] (23w) Medical staff also found necrosis on his liver as well, which suggested an impairment of liver mitochondria— Howard: —The powerhouse of the cell!
[87] (5w) Brew: —due to B. cereus.
[88] (20w) Not only that, after testing his bile and the pan that reheated the spaghetti, staff found more B. cereus cultures.
[89] (10w) He succumbed to the same fate as the young girl.
[90] (13w) Bacteria in his food killed the cells in his liver, ending his life.
[91] (15w) But what is B. cereus, and how did it take the lives of two children?
[92] (28w) According to the British Columbia Centre for Disease Control, B. cereus is a foodborne pathogen that can create two different toxins, which can trigger two kinds of illness.
[93] (20w) The first is an emetic toxin, which causes vomiting, and the second is a diarrhoeal toxin, which triggers, well, diarrhea.
[94] (24w) The emetic toxin causes vomiting almost immediately after ingestion, whereas the diarrhoeal only begins to wreak havoc once toxins are produced in the intestine.
[95] (12w) Symptoms of emetic syndrome include vomiting, nausea, and occasionally diarrhea as well.
[96] (14w) They usually appear between half an hour to 5 hours after eating contaminated food.
[97] (12w) The diarrhoeal syndrome triggers nausea, and abdominal pain, along with the diarrhea.
[98] (19w) Symptoms of diarrhoeal syndrome are more delayed compared to the emetic toxin, taking about 8 hours to start showing.
[99] (13w) It should go without saying, but some cases are more severe than others.
[100] (13w) As we saw with both of our cases, your condition can deteriorate quickly.
[101] (19w) The young girl died within 13 hours, and the young man only 2 days after ingesting the contaminated food.
[102] (12w) If you have serious symptoms, you should speak with a doctor immediately.
[103] (30w) Bacillus cereus is a bacteria commonly found in soil, and can be found on lots of different foods, including, but not limited to, meats, cereal, vegetables, milk, puddings and soups.
[104] (20w) The tenaciousness of the bacteria is due to its production of heat resistant spores, which can survive the cooking process.
[105] (23w) They are associated with starchy foods like pastas, grow in environments with pH levels more than 4.8, and temperatures between 8 and 55ºC.
[106] (17w) That being said, not all strains of the bacteria produce the toxin that actually causes food poisoning.
[107] (17w) In most cases, the reasons for B. cereus poisoning are caused by improper food handling and storage.
[108] (14w) You can kill the spores of the bacteria by cooking at temperatures above 121ºC.
[109] (20w) However, if you let your food sit out between 4 and 57ºC., the bacteria can begin producing toxins once more.
[110] (8w) As always, you must store perishable foods properly.
[111] (11w) That is, cold food below 4ºC, and hot food above 57ºC.
[112] (24w) Any amount of time food spends in the “danger zone” that is, between 4ºC and 57ºC, is time that foodborne diseases can take hold.
[113] (13w) It should be mentioned that of all foodborne diseases in the US B.
[114] (8w) cereus only accounted for 0.2% of all illnesses.
[115] (10w) Also, it’s never recommended to eat anything that smells off.
[116] (25w) Reminding you all to store food properly seems obvious, but what is a little less clear is just how this bacteria actually ctrl-alt-deletes your liver.
[117] (22w) In both of our cases above, the victims suffered from the effects of B. cereus’s emetic toxin, a little number called cereulide.
[118] (12w) How cereulide functions has actually been a mystery for a long time.
[119] (22w) The only method researchers knew to detect it used living primates, and the ethics of using our closest evolutionary cousins is questionable.
[120] (17w) However, recently better detection methods were developed that have allowed us to detail its structure more clearly.
[121] (54w) We do still have some way to go before we understand the biosynthetic pathway and mechanics of this toxin, but researchers discovered that cereulide affects the vagus nerve, the main controller of your parasympathetic nervous system, which controls some of the involuntary actions of our body, including digestion, heart rate, and the immune system.
[122] (12w) Cereulide causes vomiting because of its effect on gastrointestinal vagal afferent fibres.
[123] (23w) These nerves transmit information about the status of your gastrointestinal tract to your brain, and they control the induction of nausea and vomiting.
[124] (11w) Cereulide causes more than vomiting, as we’ve seen in our cases.
[125] (14w) The really dangerous thing about B. cereus is its toxin’s effect on the liver.
[126] (35w) A study titled, “Pathological effect of synthetic cereulide, an emetic toxin of Bacillus cereus, is reversible in mice” looked at the effect of cereulide on mitochondria after administering different levels of the toxin to mice.
[127] (24w) Their team found that cereulide works the same in mice as it does in human cases, at least as far as liver failure goes.
[128] (17w) They noticed damage in the liver within 6 hours of injecting the mice with their synthetic cereulide.
[129] (10w) They didn’t see any damage to any other organs however.
[130] (23w) In the liver itself, they found that cereulide damaged hepatocytes, the main functioning cells of the liver, forming about 80% of its mass.
[131] (33w) The extent of the damage is determined by the concentrations of cereulide consumed, but researchers found the effects of the toxin on mitochondria was the main cause of liver failure in their mice.
[132] (12w) Researchers wanted to learn if liver damage caused by cereulide is reversible.
[133] (14w) Fortunately, they found that poisoned tissue reverted to almost normal in about 4 weeks.
[134] (17w) If the load on their liver could be reduced, many patients would see improvements in their prognoses.
[135] (33w) Treatments for liver failure include medications that fight poisoning, relieve pressure in the brain, prevent bleeding, and nutritional support if your liver has been damaged such that it can no longer metabolize nutrients.
[136] (20w) As a last resort, done only when the damage is too far gone, doctors can also perform a liver transplant.
[137] (9w) Like most foodborne illnesses, your best protection is prevention.
[138] (17w) Storing all food at a safe temperature, will make sure that no nefarious microscopic bacteria can grow.
[139] (16w) It’s also just a general good rule of thumb to never eat anything that smells funny.
[140] (24w) Detecting smell is one of our body’s many defense mechanisms, and we should be mindful when our bodies tell us that something isn’t right.
[141] (25w) I’m sure that none of this is any solace to the families of those who’ve passed away as result of B. cereus and cereulide poisoning.
[142] (23w) Any death is a tragedy, but when it comes from such an innocuous place as some leftover pasta, it hurts so much more.
[143] (17w) One lapse of judgment, or one mistake can be all it takes for catastrophe to take hold.
[144] (18w) Remember, to smell your best, Scentbird is offering 55% off your first order using our coupon code, BREWS55.
[145] (8w) Or click the link in the description below!"
`;
